1 towa rd others is the only solution. We remember this day because we
2 choose a different future moving forward. We see what violence and
3 hatred brings, and we declare we will not pick up the same offense
4 but will instead plant seeds of love and hope in its place. May we
5 rebuild and replant only from this foundation; and
6 WHEREAS, we decree the Oklahoma City National Memorial will not
7 just be a place to mourn the dead and to pity the lives lost. We
8 mourn with those who mourn and extend and receive comfort. But we
9 decree this will be a place to restart hope for a better and more
10 peaceful future. It will not be a place of rekindling anger toward
11 terrorists, which gives the darkness power. It will instead be a
12 place where light dispels darkness; love dispels fear; hope dispels
13 despair; and
14 WHEREAS, we resolve that while we will not be cowed by
15 terrorists, we will not respond in a like spirit; and
16 WHEREAS, we commemorate this day in advance of the 30th
17 anniversary of the bombing of the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building
18 in Oklahoma City. We do so not in vain, thinking nothing has truly
19 changed in the hearts of men and women in the last 30 years,
20 believing that we are more divided now than perhaps any time in
21 history. We do so instead with the hope that, with divine help, we
22 can begin to truly love our brothers and sisters and move past the
23 hatred that so easily divides us. We bless those who persecute us
24 and despitefully use us, not because we don't desire justice, but
